8.  Administration  and  Procurement  Specialist  (1  position,  12  person-months). 
Responsibilities include the following: 

(i)  Assist  team  leader,  P&D,  and  Pakistan  Resident  Mission  to  establish  and 
maintain periodic procurement plans for contracting and supervising technical 
support financed under ADB TAs and loan projects; 
(ii)  Ensure that procurement systems are consistent with Government  and ADB 
guidelines for contracting and procuring goods and services; 
(iii)  Maintain accurate and current records of all contracts, certifications, payments, 
and records; 
(iv)  Assist the consultants prepare and deliver orientation and training to government, 
ADB, and other donor representatives on the results of technical studies and 
other activities supported by the TA; 
(v)  Assist the team leader provide adequate and timely reports to ADB on efficiency 
and effectiveness of ADB TA grant resources;  
(vi)       Prepare monthly and other work plans and reports as required and submit them 
through the TA 4207-PAK: team leader to the TA project director. 

C.  Provincial  Civil-Society  Coordinators  (3  province  positions,  18  person-months). 
Responsibilities include the following: 

(i)  Strengthen coordination between the federal and provincial planning agencies 
and civil society; 
(ii)  Facilitate tripartite linkages between the Government, ADB, and civil society; 
(iii)  Assist  provincial  agencies  organize,  facilitate,  and  document  project-specific 
consultations; 
(iv)  Facilitate effective civil-society inputs to ongoing and pipeline ADB TA grant and 
lending operations; 
(v)  Develop and maintain a database of civil-society contacts for provincial agencies 
and ADB mission leaders; 
(vi)  Identify and suggest innovative solutions based on best practices for engaging 
civil society in alignment of development assistance to devolution; 
(vii)  Prepare monthly and other work plans and reports as required and submit them 
through the TA 4207-PAK: team leader to the TA project director.
